                    </button>
                    <div id="faq5" class="px-6 py-5 hidden bg-gradient-to-br from-pink-50 to-rose-50 text-gray-800">
                        Property division upon divorce in South Africa depends entirely on your **marriage regime**:
                        <ul>
                            <li>•   **In Community of Property:** All assets and liabilities acquired before and during the marriage are generally shared equally (50/50 split), regardless of who acquired them.</li>
                            <li>•   **Out of Community of Property without Accrual:** Each spouse retains their separate assets and liabilities, as specified in their antenuptial contract. There is generally no sharing of assets acquired during the marriage, unless specific contributions are proven.</li>
                            <li>•   **Out of Community of Property with Accrual:** Each spouse retains their pre-marital assets, but assets accumulated during the marriage (the "accrual") are shared equally at divorce. The accrual is the growth in value of each spouse's estate during the marriage, less their initial assets.</li>
                        </ul>
                        Complex assets like the matrimonial home, pension funds (subject to the "clean-break" principle), and business interests require specific valuation and consideration. Courts aim for a fair distribution considering each party's contributions and future needs.
                    </div>
